[[Field marshal (United Kingdom)|Field Marshal]] '''John Colborne, 1st Baron Seaton''', [[Order of the Bath|GCB]], [[Order of St Michael and St George|GCMG]], [[Royal Guelphic Order|GCH]], [[Privy Council of Ireland|PC]] (16 February 1778 &ndash; 17 April 1863) was a [[British Army]] officer and Colonial Governor. After taking part as a junior officer in the [[Anglo-Russian invasion of Holland]], [[Ralph Abercromby|Sir Ralph Abercromby]]'s [[French campaign in Egypt and Syria|expedition to Egypt]] and then the [[War of the Third Coalition]], he served as military secretary to [[John Moore (British Army officer)|Sir John Moore]] at the [[Battle of Corunna]]. He then commanded the 2nd Battalion of the [[66th (Berkshire) Regiment of Foot|66th Regiment of Foot]] and, later, the [[52nd (Oxfordshire) Regiment of Foot|52nd Regiment of Foot]] at many of the battles of the [[Peninsular War]]. At the [[Battle of Waterloo]], Colborne on his own initiative brought the 52nd Regiment of Foot forward, took up a flanking position in relation to the [[Imperial Guard (Napoleon I)|French Imperial Guard]] and then, after firing repeated volleys into their flank, charged at the Guard so driving them back in disorder. He went on to become commander-in-chief of all the armed forces in British North America, personally leading the offensive at the [[Battle of Saint-Eustache]] in [[Lower Canada]] and defeating the [[Lower Canada Rebellion|rebel]] force in December 1837. After that he was [[List of Lord High Commissioners of the Ionian Islands|high commissioner of the Ionian Islands]] and then [[Commander-in-Chief, Ireland]].

==Early career==
Born the only son of Samuel Colborne and Cordelia Anne Colborne (n<U+00E9>e Garstin), Colborne was educated at [[Christ's Hospital]] in [[London]] and at [[Winchester College]].<ref name=dcb>{{Cite DCB|4359}}</ref> He was commissioned as an [[Ensign (rank)|ensign]] in the [[Lancashire Fusiliers|20th Regiment of Foot]] on 10 July 1794 securing all subsequent steps in his regimental promotion without [[Purchase of commissions in the British army|purchase]].<ref name=heath90>Heathcote, p. 90</ref> Promoted to [[lieutenant]] on 4 September 1795 and to [[captain lieutenant]] on 11 August 1799, he saw action at the [[Battle of Alkmaar (1799)|Battle of Alkmaar]] in October 1799, where he was wounded, during the [[Anglo-Russian invasion of Holland]].<ref name=heath90/> Promoted to brevet [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|captain]] on 12 January 1800, he took part in [[Ralph Abercromby|Sir Ralph Abercromby]]'s [[French campaign in Egypt and Syria|expedition to Egypt]] in August 1801 and was wounded again.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=15182|supp=|startpage=938|date=16 September 1799|accessdate=26 January 2014}}</ref>

Colborne was deployed with his regiment to [[Italy]] where he distinguished himself at the [[Battle of Maida]] in July 1806 during the [[War of the Third Coalition]].<ref name=heath90/> He became military secretary to General [[Henry Edward Fox|Henry Fox]] in 1806 and then became military secretary to [[John Moore (British Army officer)|Sir John Moore]] with the rank of [[major]] on 21 January 1808.<ref name=heath90/> In this capacity he accompanied Moore to Sweden in May 1808 and to Portugal in 1808 and served with him at the [[Battle of Benavente]] in December 1808 and [[Battle of Corunna]] in January 1809.<ref name=heath90/> It was Moore's dying request that Colborne should be given a [[lieutenant colonel]]cy and this was complied with on 2 February 1809.<ref name=heath90/> He transferred to the [[66th (Berkshire) Regiment of Foot|66th Regiment of Foot]] on 2 November 1809, and after returning to Spain with [[Arthur Wellesley, 1st Duke of Wellington|Sir Arthur Wellesley]]'s Army, he witnessed the defeat of the Spaniards at the [[Battle of Oca<U+00F1>a]] later that month.<ref name=heath91>Heathcote, p. 91</ref> He commanded a brigade at the [[Battle of Bussaco]] in September 1810 and then commanded the 2nd Battalion of the 66th Regiment of Foot at the [[Battle of Albuera]] in May 1811 where his battalion was severely mauled by the [[French Army]].<ref name=odnb>{{cite web|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/5835?docPos=1|title=John Colborne, 1st Baron Seaton|publisher=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography|accessdate=26 December 2014}}</ref> After transferring to the command of the [[52nd (Oxfordshire) Regiment of Foot|52nd Regiment of Foot]] he took part in the [[Siege of Ciudad Rodrigo (1812)|Siege of Ciudad Rodrigo]] in January 1812 where he was badly injured and had to be invalided back to England.<ref name=heath91/>

After recovering in England, Colborne returned to Spain and commanded the 52nd Regiment of Foot at the [[Siege of San Sebasti<U+00E1>n]] in August 1813 before taking temporary charge of the 2nd brigade of the Light Division in late 1813 and commanding it at the [[Battle of the Bidassoa (1813)|Battle of the Bidassoa]] in October 1813, at the [[Battle of Nivelle]] in November 1813 and at the [[Battle of the Nive]] in December 1813.<ref name=heath91/> He returned to the 52nd Regiment of Foot and commanded it at the [[Battle of Orthez]] in February 1814 and at the [[Battle of Toulouse (1814)|Battle of Toulouse]] in April 1814 and at the [[Battle of Bayonne]] also in April 1814.<ref name=heath91/> He was appointed a [[Order of the Bath|Knight Commander of the Order of the Bath]] on 4 January 1815.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=16972|supp=|startpage=20|date=4 January 1815|accessdate=26 January 2014}}</ref>

Colborne became [[aide-de-camp]] to the [[George IV of the United Kingdom|Prince Regent]] with the rank of [[colonel]] on 4 June 1814,<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=16906|supp=|startpage=1182|date=7 June 1814|accessdate=26 January 2014}}</ref> and, following [[Napoleon]]'s escape from [[Elba]], he managed to dissuade the Prince from attacking the French Army until the Duke of Wellington arrived.<ref name=heath91/> At the [[Battle of Waterloo]] in June 1815 during the [[Hundred Days]], Colborne on his own initiative brought the 52nd Regiment of Foot forward, took up a flanking position in relation to the [[Imperial Guard (Napoleon I)|French Imperial Guard]] and then, after firing repeated volleys into their flank, charged at the Guard so driving them back in disorder.<ref name=dcb/> He was appointed a Knight of the Austrian [[Military Order of Maria Theresa]] on 2 August 1815.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=17064|supp=|startpage=1941|date=23 September 1815|accessdate=26 January 2014}}</ref> After the War he remained with his regiment as part of the Army of Occupation.<ref name=odnb/>

==Canada==
[[File:Battle of Saint-Eustache.JPG|300px|thumb|right|Colborne's troops scatter the insurgents and torch the church at the [[Battle of Saint-Eustache]]]]
Colborne became [[Lieutenant Governor of Guernsey]] in July 1821<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=17737|supp=|startpage=1682|date=14 August 1821|accessdate=26 January 2014}}</ref> and, having been promoted to [[major-general]] on 27 May 1825,<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=18141|supp=|startpage=926|date=28 May 1825|accessdate=26 January 2014}}</ref> became [[List of lieutenant governors of Ontario|Lieutenant Governor of Upper Canada]] in August 1828.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=18496|supp=|startpage=1552|date=15 August 1828|accessdate=26 January 2014}}</ref> As Lieutenant Governor, Colborne increased the population of the province by 70% by initiating an organised system of immigration to bring in settlers from [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|Britain]].<ref name=odnb/> He also aided settlement by expanding the communication and transportation infrastructure through a campaign to build roads and bridges.<ref name=dcb/> He brought changes to the structure of the legislative council, increased fiscal autonomy and encouraged greater independence in the judiciary.<ref name=dcb/> In 1829 he founded [[Upper Canada College]] as a school based on the [[Elizabeth College, Guernsey]] model to educate boys in preparation for becoming leaders of the colonies.<ref name=dcb/>
[[File:Johncolborne.jpg|200px|thumb|left|Statue of John Colborne at Peninsula Barracks in [[Winchester]]]][[File:UCC Seaton statue.JPG|300px|thumb|right|Statue of John Colborne at [[Upper Canada College]]]]

In January 1836 Colborne became commander-in-chief of all the armed forces in British North America.<ref name=dcb/> He was promoted to the local rank of [[lieutenant general]] on 8 July 1836.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=19398|supp=|startpage=1249|date=8 July 1836|accessdate=26 January 2014}}</ref> During Colborne's period of office as commander-in-chief, the [[Family Compact]] promoted resistance to the political principle of [[responsible government]].<ref name=Canada>Lee, p. 149</ref> At the end of its lifespan, the Compact would be condemned by [[John Lambton, 1st Earl of Durham|Lord Durham]] as "a petty corrupt insolent Tory clique".<ref name=Canada/> This resistance, together with conflicts between the assembly and the executive over fiscal matters as well as a difficult economic situation, led to the [[Rebellions of 1837]].<ref name=dcb/> Colborne personally led the offensive at the [[Battle of Saint-Eustache]] in December 1837 defeating the [[Lower Canada Rebellion|rebel]] force which had become holed up in a church.<ref name=dcb/> 

Colborne was advanced to [[Order of the Bath|Knight Grand Cross of the Order of the Bath]] on 29 January 1838<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=19585|supp=|startpage=214|date=30 January 1838|accessdate=26 January 2014}}</ref> and, following [[Archibald Acheson, 2nd Earl of Gosford|Lord Gosford]]'s resignation in February 1838, he received additional powers as acting [[List of Governors General of Canada|Governor General of British North America]].<ref name=dcb/> Promoted to the substantive rank of lieutenant-general on 28 June 1838,<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=19631|supp=|startpage=1489|date=3 July 1838|accessdate=26 January 2014}}</ref> he put down a second revolt in October 1838 and was confirmed as [[List of Governors General of Canada|Governor General of British North America]] on 14 December 1838.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=19686|supp=|startpage=2887|date=14 December 1838|accessdate=26 January 2014}}</ref> He left Canada in October 1839 and, after arriving back in England, was raised to the [[peerage]] as '''Baron Seaton''' of Seaton in Devonshire on 5 December 1839.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=19801|supp=|startpage=2564|date=6 December 1839|accessdate=26 January 2014}}</ref>

==Later life==
Colborne became [[List of Lord High Commissioners of the Ionian Islands|high commissioner of the Ionian Islands]] in February 1843,<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=20197|supp=|startpage=553|date=17 February 1843|accessdate=26 January 2014}}</ref> and having been promoted to full [[general]] on 20 June 1854,<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=21564|supp=|startpage=1931|date=22 June 1854|accessdate=26 January 2014}}</ref> he became [[Commander-in-Chief, Ireland]] in 1855.<ref name=heath91/> After standing down from active service in Spring 1860, he was promoted to [[Field marshal (United Kingdom)|field marshal]] on 1 April 1860<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=22371|supp=|startpage=1253|date=30 March 1860|accessdate=26 January 2014}}</ref> and retired to his home at Beechwood House in [[Sparkwell]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/descriptions/959960|title=Plympton St Mary|publisher=A vision of Britain|accessdate=26 January 2014}}</ref>

Colborne also served as honorary colonel of the [[94th Regiment of Foot]],<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=19220|supp=|startpage=2244|date=12 December 1834|accessdate=26 January 2014}}</ref> as honorary colonel of the [[26th (Cameronian) Regiment of Foot]]<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=19602|supp=|startpage=783|date=30 March 1838|accessdate=26 January 2014}}</ref> and then as honorary colonel of the [[2nd Regiment of Life Guards]].<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=21534|supp=|startpage=937|date=24 March 1854|accessdate=26 January 2014}}</ref> He was also colonel-in-chief of the [[Rifle Brigade (Prince Consort's Own)]].<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=22598|supp=|startpage=774|date=14 February 1862|accessdate=26 January 2014}}</ref> He died at Valletta House in [[Torquay]] on 17 April 1863 and was buried in the churchyard of Holy Cross Church at [[Newton Ferrers]].<ref name=odnb/> 

In November 1866 a bronze statue of Colborne sculpted by [[George Gammon Adams|George Adams]] and financed by public donations was erected at Mount Wise at [[Devonport, Devon|Devonport]]: it was moved to Seaton Barracks in [[Crownhill]] in the early 1960s and then to Peninsula Barracks in [[Winchester]] in the 1990s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.devonportonline.co.uk/historic_devonport/military/seaton/lord-seaton.aspx|title= Statue of Field Marshal Lord Seaton|publisher=Devonport on line|accessdate=26 January 2014}}</ref> A second statue of Colborne also sculpted by George Adams was erected at [[Upper Canada College]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/toronto/sir-john-colborne/article16502119/|title=What Toronto's citizens of stone tell us about our history|publisher=Globe & Mail|date=24 January 2014|accessdate=26 January 2014}}</ref>

==Family==
In 1813 Colborne married Elizabeth Yonge; they had three daughters and five sons.<ref name=heath91/>

